<TEXT>
federal researchers working in secret have 
succeeded in igniting a nuclear fusion reaction in tiny pellets of 
hydrogen by using radiation from an exploding nuclear weapon 
according to a published report 
the new york times citing scientists and officials who spoke on 
condition of anonymity reported in its monday editions that the 
successful experiment occurred about two years ago at an 
underground nuclear test site in nevada 
the results have triggered a dispute over how experiments in 
smallscale fusion or microfusion should proceed the 
newspaper said 
scientists have long tried to tame nuclear fusion reactions in 
the hope they could eventually lead to an unlimited and relatively 
cheap source of electrical power in fusion reactions which are 
found in stars and hydrogen bombs atoms are joined together to 
release energy they contrast with fission reactions in which atoms 
are split rather than combined 
in most cases the scientists have tried to use concentrated 
light from giant lasers to trigger a fusion reaction but 
laserbased fusion has never proved successful the secret 
experiment in nevada the times said instead used xray radiation 
from a nuclear weapon directed at tiny fuel pellets 
the prototype fuel pellets are glass capsules filled with 
hydrogen isotopes the times said a dozen pellets can easily fit 
on the head of a pin but their power output could be equivalent to 
hundreds of pounds of high explosives the newspaper said 
the secret achievement required more energy than expected 
scientists told the times the newspaper said scientists and 
government officials are arguing over which direction fusion 
research should go 
some say the laserbased microfusion program needs a radical 
change of course the times reported while others say the nuclear 
approach while unconventional was a milestone that generated 
valuable data that will help make fusion practical 
the times said it is believed that the experiments have never 
been publicly disclosed it said that last september sheldon 
kahalas director of the nations microfusion effort told a 
princeton university conference that the effort had reached a 
historical turning point but refused to elaborate 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

