borrowers rights provisions of the 
farm credit foreclosure law are being tested by a couples attempt 
to buy back the farm they lost in foreclosure 
a class action lawsuit in federal court by james and maureen 
leckband could affect the sales of hundreds of farms that the 
federal land bank of st paul has taken from delinquent borrowers 
the farm credit rescue law which took effect jan 6 says that 
when federal land banks decide to sell farms they must give former 
owners 15 days to buy back the land the leckbands case is viewed 
as a test of what the price should be 
a public sale of their 320acre farm near worthington was 
interrupted friday with word that the lawsuit had been filed in st 
paul leaving confusion about the validity of the sale 
the leckbands claim they are entitled to buy the farm at its 
current appraised value the bank maintains the land is worth the 
maximum offer it draws from interested buyers 
the difference can be significant now that farmland values are 
rising expectations that prices will climb can generate bids well 
over appraisal estimates 
attorneys for the bank said they had not seen the complaint and 
would not comment specifically on the case 
but in general we think fair market value is what somebody is 
willing to pay for it under a competitive bidding process said 
william collins general counsel for the st paul district of farm 
credit services which includes the bank 
in addition to the specific issue of the leckbands rights the 
suit seeks to place responsibility with national farm credit 
administration officials for interpreting the law evenly throughout 
the country the leckbands attorney james massey said the omaha 
district of the farm credit administration has given borrowers 
rights his clients are seeking 
the suit names several national and local fcs officials as well 
as the bank 
the leckbands who raise crops and livestock borrowed 316800 
between 1980 and 1983 according to the complaint after they fell 
behind on their payments the bank foreclosed on jan 13 1987 the 
leckbands were allowed to keep the property during a oneyear 
redemption period 
