<TEXT>
scientists have ignited a nuclear fusion 
reaction in tiny pellets of hydrogen by using radiation from an 
exploding nuclear weapon raising hopes for an unlimited source of 
energy a newspaper reported today 
the successful experiment viewed as a major advance toward 
determining the possibility of harnessing smallscale fusion 
occurred about two years ago at an underground nuclear test site in 
nevada according to the new york times 
the us government kept it secret because it did not want 
foreign countries to know about it but some details have been 
discussed at scientific conferences the newspaper said 
while revealing nuclear fusion as a potentially highly potent 
energy source the results have triggered a dispute over how 
experiments in smallscale fusion or microfusion should 
proceed the newspaper said 
scientists have long tried to tame nuclear fusion reactions in 
the hope they could eventually lead to an unlimited and relatively 
cheap source of electricity in fusion reactions which are found 
in stars and hydrogen bombs atoms are joined together to release 
energy they contrast with fission reactions in which atoms are 
split rather than combined 
in most cases the scientists have tried to use concentrated 
light from giant lasers to trigger a fusion reaction but 
laserbased fusion has never proved successful the secret 
experiment in nevada the times said instead used xray radiation 
from a nuclear weapon directed at tiny fuel pellets 
the prototype fuel pellets are glass capsules filled with 
hydrogen isotopes the times said a dozen pellets can easily fit 
on the head of a pin but their power output could be equivalent to 
hundreds of pounds of high explosives the newspaper said 
the secret achievement required more energy than expected 
scientists told said 
some scientists say the laserbased microfusion program needs a 
radical change of course while others say the nuclear approach 
while unconventional was a milestone that generated valuable data 
that will help make fusion practical the newspaper said 
nuclear fusion could be used to develop antimissile weapons and 
perhaps become a cheap source of boundless electric power the 
report said 
the times said the experiments were believed to have never been 
publicly disclosed it noted that last september sheldon kahalas 
director of the nations microfusion effort told a princeton 
university conference that the effort had reached a historical 
turning point but refused to elaborate 
</TEXT>
