<TEXT>
commuter buses from soweto 
were deserted today and four buses near durban were firebombed as 
hundreds of thousands of blacks joined the first nationwide protest 
strike since major opposition groups were banned last month 
in other violence police fired tear gas at a predominantly 
indian university and arrested students who tried to force others 
to join the boycott the strike was organized in defiance of 
emergency regulations to commemorate the 28th anniversary of a 
massacre in the township of sharpeville and to protest the banning 
of any activity by the united democratic front and 16 other 
antiapartheid groups 
police estimated 40 percent of the black work force in the 
johannesburg region stayed away from their jobs but did not give a 
figure for the number involved 
in sharpeville residents placed flowers at graves of some of 
the 69 massacre victims and held memorial services 
winnie mandela wife of jailed african national congress leader 
nelson mandela attended one of the services after arriving in the 
township south of johannesburg in a bus with other activists 
there was an unconfirmed report police ordered the bus to leave 
but mrs mandela said her group left voluntarily 
in soweto the black township of 25 million people outside 
johannesburg virtually no passengers boarded commuter buses 
according to cheryl roxmouth of the putco bus company normal daily 
ridership is about 75000 
schools and most shops in soweto were closed and residents said 
few of the hundreds of minibus taxis which carry many sowetans to 
work were operating 
south african transport services said ridership on its trains 
during morning rush hour was down by up to 20 percent it dismissed 
as inaccurate an earlier press report that said ridership was down 
by about 80 percent 
in durban four putco buses were firebombed prompting putco to 
halt service in several townships when drivers refused to work 
