<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive 
bidding on government contracts setting the stage for a new ruling 
on the boundaries between congressional and presidential powers 
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments 
challenging the comptroller generals role in administering the 
1984 competition in contracting act 
the case raises issues similar to those in the constitutional 
fight over the grammrudman deficitcutting law 
the case stems from rejection by the us army corps of 
engineers of a low bid submitted by ameron inc a new jersey 
company to repair sewer lines at the united states military 
academy at west point ny 
although ameron submitted a bid of 103 million some 200000 
less than the next lowest bidder it was rejected by the corps 
because of a problem with the bond supporting the bid 
ameron protested the rejection under provisions of the 1984 
competition in contracting act 
the law empowers the comptroller general a congressional 
watchdog to suspend the award of contracts and to award 
bidpreparation costs and attorneys fees to companies that 
successfully challenge the rejection of their bids 
the law was prompted by alleged excess costs of awarding many 
lucrative government contracts without competitive bidding the 
laws supporters said that in fiscal 1983 the government awarded 
114 billion in noncompetitive contracts out of a total of 168 
billion 
administration lawyers said the powers given the comptroller 
general in the 1984 law are unconstitutional under the supreme 
courts 1986 ruling in the grammrudman case 
in that decision the justices struck down the core provision of 
the deficitreduction law because it designated the comptroller 
general as the official with power to set acrosstheboard budget 
cuts the court said such a function impermissibly blurs the line 
separating the legislative and executive branches 
the comptroller general is appointed by the president but can be 
removed from office only by congress 
in the dispute over contract bidding the 3rd us circuit court 
of appeals said the comptroller generals powers under the 1984 law 
are within constitutional bounds 
the appeals court said the law rather than concentrating power 
in the legislative branch diffuses and divides power giving 
final control over procurement decisions to the executive but 
permitting meaningful oversight by an agent of congress 
it said the comptroller general legitimately may delay contract 
awards to assure that federal procurement officials pay attention 
to his recommendations 
the law is aimed at counteracting the apparent willingness of 
procuring agencies to frustrate congressional inquiry by rushing to 
complete challenged procurement projects the appeals court added 
justice department lawyers told the high court that the law 
gives the comptroller general nonlegislative powers to determine 
the timing of a contract between an agency of the executive 
branch and a private party 
the law was defended by comptroller general charles a bowsher 
and by democratic and republican leaders of congress 
the case is army corps of engineers vs ameron 87163 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

