<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to reinstate a 
150000 libel award won and then lost by a joplin mo 
policeman against his local newspaper 
the justices without comment let stand rulings that officer 
don r speer failed to prove the joplin globe acted with actual 
malice when it accused him in an editorial of using excessive 
force 
the controversy stems from an april 23 1983 demonstration 
outside a downtown joplin bar 
about two dozen protesters picketed the bar that evening because 
most of its patrons were homosexual 
speer was sent to arrest the demonstrators because they had not 
obtained a parade permit 
while making the arrests speer got into an altercation with max 
mccoy a globe reporter who was taking photographs of the 
demonstration and arrests 
mccoy who sustained injuries and whose camera was broken told 
globe editors that speer and other police officers used excessive 
force 
an april 24 article reflected both mccoys and the polices 
versions of the incident 
an editorial published two days later condemned speers conduct 
stating that while mccoy was cuffed and defenseless the officers 
continued to strike him kick him 
speer sued the papers publisher ottaway newspapers inc in 
federal court contending that the editorial had libeled him 
a jury awarded him 100000 in compensatory damages and 50000 
in punitive damages but the trial judge threw out the award the 
judge ruled that speer treated as a public figure for purposes of 
the lawsuit had not proved actual malice 
public figures who sue for libel must prove that the statement 
was false and published with knowledge or reckless disregard of its 
falsity private individuals who sue for libel have an easier task 
they must prove the statement was false and published through 
negligence 
in upholding the trial judges ruling the 8th us circuit 
court of appeals ruled last sept 9 that mccoy had nothing to do 
with publication of the editorial at issue 
a finding of institutional actual malice by the globe may not 
be based only on mccoys state of mind the appeals court said 
it added that globe editors knew mccoy as a trusted employee 
and believed him to be reliable honest and good with details 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for speer argued that the 
appeals court ruling will spur newspapers to compartmentalize 
their factfinding and writing functions since liability can only 
be imposed by persons occupying the latter status 
the appeal added rewarding a newspaper for the calculated 
deceit of an employee it retains to gather information 
constitutes an unnecessary denigration of the individuals right to 
the protection of his own good name 
the case is speer vs ottaway newspapers 87942 
