<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let the 
dalkon shields maker set up a 15 million emergency fund to help 
women who say the contraceptive device left them infertile 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that blocks 
creation of the fund pending the outcome ofbankruptcy proceedings 
for ah robins which manufactures the device 
in a related case the court refused to review a ruling that at 
least temporarily barred some dalkon shield users from suing aetna 
casualty amp surety co which insures ah robins for liability 
claims 
robins facing massive damage claims from hundreds of thousands 
of women filed for bankruptcy in 1985 to protect the companys 
assets its intrauterine device allegedly caused pelvic 
inflammation spontaneous abortions infertility and in a few 
cases death 
robins filed for bankruptcy under what is known as chapter 11 a 
law that allows debtors to protect assets while repaying debts 
under a courtdevised plan 
the company stopped marketing the dalkon shield in 1974 but did 
not actually recall the product until 1984 
robins reported on march 7 that it had a fourthquarter loss of 
169 billion in 1987 due to funds set aside for dalkon shield 
injury claims the company reported an 818 million profit for the 
year 
the case acted on today involving the 15 million fund centered 
on an attempt by robins to trim some of its losses and to provide 
immediate money for women who could undergo corrective surgery or 
become pregnant through in vitro fertilization 
that procedure involves fertilizing the womans egg outside her 
womb 
robins said the surgery costing approximately 15000 per 
woman or the in vitro procedure would give women approaching the 
end of their safe childbearing years a chance to have children 
many claimants who used the dalkon shield when it was 
introduced in the early 1970s are approaching the biological 
deadline the company said it added that the emergency fund 
serves humanitarian purposes and makes good business sense because 
it could reduce claims against robins by women whose fertility is 
restored 
lawyers representing women suing the company also supported the 
idea the fund was approved last may 21 by us district judge 
robert r merhige jr in richmond va who is presiding over 
nationwide claims against robins 
merhige separately has ordered robins to create a 248 billion 
trust fund to pay some 200000 claims against the company robins 
had paid 500 million in damages before filing for bankruptcy 
in a related development american home products corp is 
proposing to take over robins for 3 billion 
the emergency 15 million fund that is the subject of todays 
supreme court action was opposed by owners of robins stock on nov 
3 the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled in the stockholders 
favor 
the appeals court said the federal bankruptcy code prohibits 
creation of the emergency fund because it would give preferential 
treatment to some with claims against robins the money cannot be 
spent while reorganization of the company is pending in bankruptcy 
proceedings the appeals court said 
in the case involving aetna federal lawsuits were filed in 
kansas and new hampshire by thousands of women seeking damages from 
the insurance company 
they said aetna was at fault because robins delegated to it 
responsibility for monitoring the performance of the dalkon shield 
and deciding whether it should be recalled the women also accused 
aetna of covering up evidence that the devices were defective 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals in september blocked the 
lawsuits at least until the bankruptcy proceedings are concluded 
the appeals court said inevitably aetna must involve robins 
in this litigation aetnas primary defense logically will be that 
robins not aetna is responsible for the injuries suffered 
the appeals court continued robins will inexorably be drawn 
into this litigation and it will detract from the 
bankruptcy process 
the cases are mabey vs official committee of equity security 
holders 871267 and oberg vs aetna 871208 
</TEXT>
