<TEXT>
angry poultry farmers threw live chickens 
and eggs at a us diplomatic office monday during a protest of 
imported american turkeys 
the 3000 farmers also took their protest to the bureau of 
foreign trade where they pelted a senior government official with 
eggs 
during the demonstration outside the american institute in 
taiwan farmers shouted we dont want us turkeys 
one protester cried out slogans are useless and the 
farmers threw 30 live chickens and dozens of eggs into the 
institute compound visa applicants reporters and policemen 
outside the building also were hit by the eggs 
farmers argue that chicken prices have fallen more than 50 
percent in five months because the united states has made taiwan a 
dumping ground for turkeys 
they gave a petition to officials at the institute which 
handles diplomatic matters between the united states and taiwan in 
the absence of formal relations 
the protesters then went to the bureau of foreign trade and 
threw eggs at vincent siew the bureaus director general when he 
spoke with the farmers but failed to promise an immediate ban on 
turkey imports 
siew told demonstrators that allowing us turkey imports was 
part of a plan to help reduce taiwans huge trade surplus with the 
united states which taipei said reached 16 billion last year 
taiwan officials want to lower the surplus to reduce us 
protectionist sentiment 
siew spoke to the farmers in a gynmasium near the bureau office 
but had to leave under riot police escort as farmers yelled step 
down vincent siew the demonstrators dispersed four hours after 
the protest began 
siew is a member of the taiwanus trade committee which 
recommended easing restrictions on us turkey imports the cabinet 
still must approve the decision 
the american institute in taiwan said us turkeys accounted for 
less than 1 percent of taiwans poultry market and did not hurt 
local farmers it said the price slump was caused by overproduction 
and inadequate distribution and marketing 
demonstration leader chen tungfang president of taiwans 
poultry association argued that chicken farmers have suffered an 
average monthly loss of 21 million since us turkey imports 
increased in november 
agriculture council officials said taiwan imported 2261 metric 
tons of turkeys from the united states last year up 142 percent 
from a year earlier 
an earlier demonstration was held wednesday when about 5000 
fruit and poultry farmers marched through taipei streets to protest 
the government decision to import turkeys and more fruit from the 
united states 
