<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
making it easier for people to use a federal antiracketeering law 
to sue businesses 
the court said it will hear an appeal by phone customers in 
minnesota who have accused northwestern bell telephone co of 
trying to bribe state public utility officials 
the phone subcribers sued the company under a law known as the 
racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act rico 
they said the company beginning in 1980 tried illegally to win 
rate increases by offering gifts employment offers tickets to 
sporting and cultural events and other favors to members of the 
minnesota public utilities commission 
the suit was thrown out by a federal judge and that ruling was 
upheld last september by the 8th us circuit court of appeals 
the appeals court said the phone users failed to allege a 
continuing pattern of racketeering activity required to make a case 
under the rico act 
a single fraudulent effort or scheme is insufficient grounds 
for a suit the appeals court said it said the phone customers 
complaint alleges no more than a series of fraudulent acts 
committed in furtherance of a single scheme to influence the 
public utility commissioners 
the supreme court is being asked to pick between various 
theories of how difficult it should be to maintain such a lawsuit 
the most expansive view would permit a rico suit when there are 
two related acts in furtherance of a single episode or a scheme 
a more restrictive view would be that a pattern of racketeering 
activity exists only when there are multiple separate criminal 
schemes or episodes 
those suing northwestern bell said there also is a middle road 
that would permit such suits based on an analysis of various 
factors including the number and variety of alleged illegal acts 
the number of victims the length of time of the activity and the 
number of participants in the alleged scheme 
they said the 8th circuit court ruling conflicts with decision 
by a number of other federal appeals courts 
the case is hj inc vs northwestern bell 871252 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

