<TEXT>
vice president george bush won 
puerto ricos republican primary and added 14 more national 
convention delegates to his tally while jesse jackson won the 
democrats nonbinding beauty contest balloting 
with 35 percent of the precincts reporting bush picked up 98 
percent of sundays vote gop rival sen bob dole of kansas had 
received just 2 percent 
bush had an overwhelming 1935 votes compared to just 48 for 
dole in ballots that had been tallied bush has the 14 
delegates said local gop chairman luis ferre 
the vast majority of puerto ricans chose to vote in the 
democratic primary with 91 percent of the precincts reporting 
jackson led with 87757 votes or 32 percent followed by 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis with 70733 for 26 percent 
illinois sen paul simon was third with 57639 votes or 21 
percent tennessee sen albert gore jr had 45361 for 17 percent 
and missouri rep richard gephardt had received 9159 or 3 percent 
of the votes 
the democratic primary had no effect on the candidates delegate 
totals for the democratic national convention next july in atlanta 
the 33 delegates at stake sunday who will choose another 18 
delegates have said they will go uncommitted to the convention 
in all puerto rico will send 56 delegates to the convention 
including gov raphael hernandez colon and four other party leaders 
who automatically receive delegate seats leaders say the 
delegation intends to vote as a bloc 
puerto ricos two main political parties hernandez colons 
popular democratic party and the outofpower new progressive 
party predicted that 1 million voters would cast ballots new 
progressives in general favor statehood for puerto rico while 
popular democrats do not 
the turnout was less than half what was expected possibily 
because the system approved by the state election commission 
required voters to register beginning at 9 am but prohibited them 
from voting until after 2 pm the system was set up to prevent 
double voting 
in 1980 the republican presidential primary was held two weeks 
before the democratic primary new progressive party voters cast 
ballots first for george bush a longtime proponent of statehood 
for puerto rico and then for jimmy carter the popular democratic 
party supported massachusetts sen edward m kennedy eight years 
ago 
gop chairman ferre said many republicans probably did not vote 
because of the confusion caused by dole backers who tried to call 
off the primary and choose delegates instead by caucus the issue 
was not settled until two days before the primary when a superior 
court judge ruled it must be held 
in preliminary figures released shortly after noon the 
commission reported the pdp slate ahead of the npp slate by 373950 
votes to 297408 with most of the 1650 polling stations 
tabulated a total of 671358 valid votes were counted 
pdp officials claimed they won at least 29 democratic convention 
delegate seats and perhaps all 33 that were at stake 
what we have seen in these primaries is a prelude of what will 
happen in november when the two parties meet again in 
gubernatorial elections said hernandez colon who is running for 
reelection 
the victory touched off pdp celebrations that included 
fireworks speeches and a merengue band at party headquarters and 
a caravan that wound its way horns tooting and loudspeakers 
blaring through the old san juan and puerta de tierra sections of 
the capital at 2 am 
ex gov carlos romero barcelo who headed the npp slate 
conceded his delegates lost but said we are not defeated the 
defeated dont continue to fight and we are in a fight against the 
pdp from today on 
romero barcelo faces a primary on june 12 against san juan mayor 
baltasar corrada del rio for the npp nomination for governor 
losing sunday may have weakened his standing in the party 
aside from a test of strength between hernandez colon and romero 
barcelo at issue was control of the local democratic party whose 
leaders will be chosen by the 33 delegates elected sunday 
the npp wants puerto rico to become the 51st us state the pdp 
wants things to remain as they are with puerto ricans as us 
citizens with almost every right and obligation except they cannot 
vote for president in the general election and do not pay federal 
taxes 
anticipating trouble between the rival parties the police 
department canceled days off and vacations and stationed 3000 
officers at or near polling stations and party offices the sale of 
alcoholic beverages was prohibited from midnight saturday to sunday 
night 
there were no reports of violence 
</TEXT>
