more than 250000 refugees of 
drought and civil war from neighboring sudan need more help to 
control disease and starvation the governmentowned news agency 
said monday 
the sudanese refugees are aggravating an existing hunger problem 
in ethiopia where 7 million people are threatened by starvation 
most live in the northern provinces of tigray and eritrea where 
ethiopia is fighting its own battle against secessionist rebels 
an average of sudanese 15 refugees died each day last month but 
the daily death toll recently had dropped to three ethiopian news 
agency said quoting one of the countrys red cross officials 
the red cross is working among seven national and international 
agencies providing food clothing and medicine to the refugees 
at least 47000 of them flooded into ethiopias western border 
regions of illubabor and wellega in the past four months the 
agency said the influx was increasing daily 
many of the refugees were fleeing a war started in 1983 by the 
southernbased sudan peoples liberation army the rebels are 
fighting the moslemdominated government in khartoum for economic 
reforms and more autonomy in the mainly christian and animist south 
that war has also worsened chronic droughts 
