<TEXT>
state rep bill english takes along a 
portable television set and earplug when he goes to the house floor 
to vote 
other lawmakers cluster around a lobby television set or around 
tvs and radios in their offices so focused on them that house 
leaders sometimes need six quorum calls to transact business 
the house is virtually at a standstill with five members 
working as the board of managers for the senates impeachment trial 
of gov evan mecham and the 55 others fascinated by testimony that 
has included an alleged death threat sexual affairs political 
paybacks and the governor himself 
the trial entered its fourth week monday and the senate has 
considered only one of three charges against mecham a firstterm 
republican who is the first us governor to be impeached in six 
decades and the first ever in arizona 
many house committees canceled meetings last week for lack of 
bills the chairmen wanted to consider and the house moved to a 
threeday week beginning monday down from fourday work weeks 
the 30member senate meanwhile has scheduled night committee 
meetings in an effort to act on the relatively few key areas 
lawmakers want to address this session the budget taxes air 
pollution and indigent health care 
regular sessions are supposed to last 100 days which generally 
would mean ending in late april but pressure to close does not 
begin in earnest until per diem pay is cut in half after 110 days 
and stops altogether after 120 days 
lawmakers say the pace has been especially slow this year 
despite promises from the house republican leadership that things 
would start moving once the house finished preimpeachment hearings 
and sent the matter to the senate 
its not been a terribly productive year so far says house 
minority leader art hamilton a democrat from phoenix 
its the most difficult session ive seen in 16 years and it 
doesnt seem to be getting any better he added citing a lot 
more emotion than probably action 
republican leaders acknowledge that impeaching a fellow 
republican has taken its toll on party unity hamilton and others 
note the inaction on major bills and the concentration on issues 
such as a resolution telling congress that soviet troops should 
quit angola 
other committee chairmen meanwhile have continued to limit 
debate prompting a series of walkouts by democrats who complain 
that important bills are not being given a full hearing 
republican leaders say they have been trying to keep the session 
as normal as possible but hamilton said he thinks lawmakers should 
take advantage of the spare time to look indepth at issues such as 
taxes arizonas medicaid alternative and pollution which normally 
get resolved on a rush basis due to the press of other business 
but because most house members are watching the trial hamilton 
said the house is doing little other its normal work at a much 
slower pace 
its tough to compete with the soapopera draw of the 
impeachment trial 
mecham is charged with ordering the department of public safety 
director not to cooperate with an investigation of the alleged 
threat by a state official against a former mecham aide the aide 
was about to testify before a state grand jury on the governors 
unreported 350000 campaign loan 
