<TEXT>
safety experts previewed a series of new 
designs for childresistant pill containers monday to highlight 
this years national poison prevention week 
the special medicine containers have helped reduce the number of 
children fatally poisoned from nearly 500 in 1962 to 56 in 1985 
reported terrence m scanlon chairman of the federal consumer 
product safety commission 
marsha millonig of the national poison prevention week said 
resistant caps are one of the three main factors in reducing 
poisonings along with the growth of poison control centers and 
improved parental awareness of the dangers of poison for children 
and dr toby litovitz of the national capital poison control 
center at georgetowen university hospital stressed that even with 
the reduction in poisonings the danger to toddlers persists and 
merits continued vigilance 
while the special caps on medicine bottles and other products 
have helped reduce the toll on children scanlon conceded that many 
adults also have trouble with them 
hugh lockhart of michigan state university described several 
possible design changes that have been developed 
the currently popular design in which the cap from a pill 
bottle must be pressed down and turned to get it open requires 
some strength and determination he noted 
basically people are required to engage a series of lugs that 
they cannot see using a principle that they do not understand 
its no wonder theyve had trouble lockhart said 
one of the findings of the university researchers is that the 
physical strength of very old people may be no greater than than of 
a small child he said but the elderly generally retain manual 
dexterity and can handle problem solving better so those abilities 
were considered in designing new closures 
among the closures being tested he said are 
placing individual pills in a strong plastic blister with a 
peeloff backing 
designing a rigid plastic package with pills in individual 
blisters the package would fold in half with a childresistant 
latch holding it closed 
bottle caps similar to the current ones except with a slot 
that a key could be slid into to allow them to be turned to open 
another bottle cap with a hole in the side into which a pencil 
or other tool could be inserted to twist it open 
a somewhat easier to open version of the current caps which is 
lifted to open rather than being pressed down 
using inks in contrasting colors to make the directions and 
arrows stand out on caps expecially those on which arrows have to 
be lined up to get them open 
safety commission vice chairwoman carol dawson said the agency 
is arranging for test samples of the various designs to be made 
and expects to give them tryouts during the next year 
designs that are successful would be made available for 
manufacturers to copy at no charge she said 
some of the designs could be more costly than current 
childresistant caps although lockhard declined to speculate on 
the amount of the cost 
the closure manufacturers association meanwhile applauded the 
research effort and said its members are anxious to participate in 
the testing of the new designs 
</TEXT>
