<TEXT>
secretary of state george p shultz opened 
wideranging talks monday in which he intends to confront visiting 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze about massive soviet 
arms shipments to central america 
they met for 90 minutes to set their agenda for the next two 
days also shevardnadze told reporters he had a very general 
review of the international situation with shultz 
the dispute over central america appeared unlikely to spoil 
progress in efforts to reduce us and soviet nuclear arms or 
preparations for the next superpower summit meeting in moscow 
shevardnadze was expected to offer a latemay summit date and to 
have it accepted by president reagan after they meet wednesday at 
the white house 
the soviet foreign minister called his first session with shultz 
organizational asked if a date for the summit would be set 
during his visit shevardnadze said i think so 
a treaty to slash us and soviet armories of longrange nuclear 
arms by 30 percent to 50 percent is the projected centerpiece of 
reagans fourth meeting with general secretary mikhail s gorbachev 
while shultz said sunday the agreement was not yet in the 
bag us and soviet experts will try to square drafts of their 
treaty proposals during shevardnadzes threeday visit 
but the wars in nicaragua and afghanistan cast a cloud on the 
presummit preprarations 
assistant secretary of state rozanne l ridgway and state 
department spokesman charles e redman accused moscow of an 
unceasing supply of weapons to the leftist government in nicaragua 
apparently referring also to the reported supply of soviet 
rifles and other arms to embattled panamanian strongman manuel 
antonio noriega from cuba ms ridgway said what we need now is 
an end to the continued soviet provision of these high levels of 
military equipment 
redman meanwhile accused the soviets of shipping more than 
3000 tons of equipment to nicaragua in january and february alone 
for a number of years the soviets have supplied nicaragua with 
500 million to 600 million in assistance annually he said i 
certainly dont see it as an issue heating up redman said but 
soviet military support is a continuing cause for concern 
in afghanistan meanwhile the united states has been arming 
rebels fighting a marxist government backed by an estimated 120000 
soviet troops and weapons 
the united states is demanding the soviets withdraw the troops 
and also end the aid negotiations between afghanistan and pakistan 
reached an impasse last week but shultz evidently was not prepared 
to seek a compromise solution with shevardnadze 
theyre the ones who got into afghanistan and the ones who 
have to figure out how they are going to get out ms ridgway 
said 
reagan at a white house ceremony to sign an afghanistan day 
proclamation approved by congress said 
we may be approaching an historic moment we all hope that 
what we hear from moscow means there will be a complete and 
irreversible withdrawal of all the soviet forces from afghanistan 
that the afghan people will be able to freely determine their own 
future and that the millions of refugees can return to their homes 
with dignity 
shultzs first session with shevardnadze dealt primarily with 
setting an agenda for their talks on tuesday and wednesday they 
will take up four main issues arms control human rights regional 
disputes and ussoviet relations generally 
that is the traditional lineup for what has become monthly 
meetings between shultz and shevardnadze alternating between 
washington and moscow 
but in a novel break with tradition instead of scheduling a 
formal dinner tuesday night shultz arranged a buffet at the state 
department simultaneously with the showing in the ben franklin 
reception room of the movie thats entertainment 
and tuesday morning a new riskreduction center will be 
opened at the state department to provide quicker communication 
between the two capitals in order to avoid accidental nuclear war 
a formal agreement was signed here last september a center is 
being established in moscow as well 
satellite links will transmit information between the two 
capitals augmenting an existing telecommunications hotline 
