<TEXT>
a canadiansoviet research team has completed 
nearly a fifth of its 1100mile trek across the arctic with only 
the anticipated problems like frostbite and blisters its 
spokeswoman said monday 
the 13 soviet and canadian team members skied 13 miles monday 
shirley smyth said by telephone from ottawa she said the team 
covered 16 miles sunday its greatest singleday distance in minus 
33 cold 
using an anglemeasuring device called a theodolite which 
resembles a surveyors transit scientists are trying to find a 
second magnetic pole on their journey over untrodden territory 
she said a canadian and soviet doctor on the 3weekold 
expedition are treating team members for frostbite and blisters 
team members took a twoday break last week to begin scientific 
tests and repair broken equipment they also varied their steady 
diet of driedmeat known as pemmican with fruit eggs and steak 
they could have a bit of a picnic said smyth it was a 
break from pemmican 
she said relations between canadians and soviets were warm and 
spirits high 
the expedition left the severnaya zemlya archipelago the 
northernmost point in the soviet union to ski and walk to the 
north pole the threemonth journey will end in canada at cape 
columbia on ellesmere island 
