<TEXT>
the world bank is asking its 151 member 
governments for an additional 224 billion in cash including 420 
million from the united states in order to raise lending to poor 
countries the banks president said monday 
the bank now lends about 14 billion a year at current rates of 
interest though for much longer periods than commercial banks 
usually do it lends an additional 3 billion annually on even 
easier terms to the poorest countries 
the new cash represents 3 percent of the banks recently 
announced 748 billion increase in capital which has been 
approved by the member governments the rest of the money would be 
on call in case the bank fell short of funds but it has never had 
to use any of its on call money in more than 40 years of 
operations 
the united states is being asked for the biggest single share of 
the new capital increase 14 billion of which 420 million would 
be in cash and the rest on call because the cash would be spread 
out over five or six years the administration is now asking 
congress for a first 70 million 
but as a former congressman who well remembers senator everett 
dirksens description of the appropriations process as a billion 
dollars here a billion dollars there and pretty soon youre 
talking about real money i do not expect or want automatic 
approval of this capital increase said bank president barber b 
conable a former republican congressman from new york 
conable said that as needs have grown in the third world 
resources to meet them have not kept pace 
he noted that in the previous five years there had been a flow 
of 65 billion from the industrial countries to the poor ones 
the reversal amounts to a crisis for development one that 
puts a duty on the world bank to be even more vigorous as an honest 
broker between rich and poor he said 
conables speech was prepared for delivery in san francisco to 
the world affairs council of northern california copies were 
distributed to reporters by the banks headquarters in washington 
</TEXT>
