<TEXT>
a downandout man who left his leanto 
shack in chicago in january to begin a new life in new mexico 
headed back to chicago on monday for another new start and perhaps 
marriage 
harold thomas boarded the bus to chicago after quitting the job 
he had been given by a couple who read of his plight and offered 
him a home in this farming and ranching community of about 11000 
people 
it was just a place to stay and a meal thomas said of the 
home he was given by roy gilman 75 and his wife ethel 68 i 
felt like a robot 
he said however that his big reason for leaving was the 
girl i was going with in chicago wants to get married 
he said the gilmans were nice people and had placed 300 in a 
bank for him but that they told him they could not afford to pay 
him for his work 
a man cant live with just room and board after three months 
with room and board you know i want to have a family and stuff 
thomas said he was going to try to find a place to stay and see 
if his brother might help him 
i think hes going to be happier with his people mrs 
gilman said monday night 
he seemed very happy here she said it seemed like he 
thought a lot of us we thought a lot of him it started out nice 
and ended nice 
thomas 35 arrived in portales on jan 17 after the gilmans 
read about him in an ap story published in the portales 
newstribune they contacted the ap bureau in chicago and said if 
thomas was willing to work theyd provide him with a home and a 
job 
the gilmans son ralph said thomas didnt give any notice he 
was quitting just telling him monday morning that he was homesick 
and was ready to go 
before gaining national attention thomas wore illfitting 
clothes and ate in soup kitchens he and another man endured 
subzero temperatures in a rotted wood and canvas shack on the banks 
of the chicago river because they said they felt safer there than 
in cityrun shelters 
by the time thomas boarded a bus for the 27hour journey to new 
mexico people had donated clothes luggage and spending money 
his new home was an 8footby30foot trailer in the junkyard 
where he worked eight hours a day six days a week tearing apart 
old cars and rebuilding engines the other day was spent working in 
the fields at a churchrun orphanage where the gilmans had 
volunteered his service 
