businesses and schools 
we think he is vulnerable said prakash karat of the marxist 
communist party of india which has helped organize some of the 
agitation if he dares to call a midterm poll snap election 
the opposition has a good chance of winning 
in karats eyes the 43yearold prime minister has brought the 
problems on himself he cited charges of corruption rising sikh 
separatist violence in punjab state and mounting economic problems 
gandhi has so far rejected calls for a snap election and aides 
and some independent analysts say the opposition parties are too 
much in disarray to beat him anyway 
the handful of factions are united only in their antigandhi 
fervor and often tend to compete more with each other no overall 
leader has emerged from among the dissidents 
the indian press alive to rumors that gandhi may indeed call an 
election has begun talking about his tina factor an acronym 
for there is no alternative supporters and detractors alike 
say tina may ensure that gandhi not only weathers the political 
storm but emerges with a second fiveyear term 
a poll of more than 10000 voters conducted in february for 
india today a biweekly news magazine indicated that if parliament 
elections were held now gandhis congress party would win 64 
percent of the seats 
that would be down from the 77 percent congress won in december 
1984 when gandhi came to power on a wave of sympathy two months 
after his mother and predecessor indira gandhi was assassinated 
by two sikh bodyguards but its more than enough to form a 
government in indias multiparty system 
rajiv gandhis congress benefits from the tina factor 
precisely because the opposition parties show no signs of coming 
together india today concluded 
ashis nandy a political analyst at the center for the study of 
developing societies doesnt agree regardless of what opinion 
polls show he said the opposition could defeat gandhi 
the indian electorate traditionally either rewards a regime 
for ruling well or punishes it for ruling badly nandy added 
although rajiv gandhi may still be personally honest he looks 
tainted looks inefficient the voters do not feel good about him 
just who would lead an opposition charge nationally remains in 
question the strongest contender is vp singh who was gandhis 
finance minister and then defense minister before being ousted from 
the congress party on grounds of antiparty activity 
singh now assails gandhi as a total failure he and a dozen 
other congress dissidents have been trying to forge alliances with 
other opposition groups no common front has emerged in part 
because leftist groups like the communist party refuse to ally 
themselves with rightwing hindudominated parties like the 
bharatiya janata party 
gandhi enjoyed a honeymoon of sorts during his first two years 
in office an airline pilot before moving into politics he 
promised to modernize india and was nicknamed mr clean for his 
pledge to bring honest government to the 800 million indians 
with the congressdominated parliament behind him gandhi 
liberalized industrial policy modified the tax system to encourage 
private investment and increased funding for education and health 
last year the honeymoon ended first came the disclosure that 
gandhis finance ministry had hired an american detective agency to 
investigate the illegal overseas bank accounts of indians a 
controversial move in a nation wary of foreign influence 
next came the announcement that the government was investigating 
alleged kickbacks paid on contracts for swedish artillery and west 
german submarines 
opposition leaders and several powerful newspapers seized the 
corruption issue and hammered away with allegations that some of 
the bribes went to gandhi or his allies in the congress party 
none of the charges were proved but gandhi was forced to go to 
parliament and deny personal involvement 
at the same time domestic problems mounted 
the annual monsoon rains failed plunging twothirds of the 
nation into drought 
attacks by sikh extremists in punjab rose dramatically leaving 
more than 1000 people dead by the end of 1987 
an indiansponsored peace accord in nearby sri lanka was signed 
but shortly collapsed although gandhi has sent more than 50000 
troops to the island to put down a tamil separatist rebellion the 
opposition has not focused on the issue 
last year there was a tremendous amount of uncertainty said 
a gandhi aide who spoke on condition of anonymity we weathered 
it since then a lot of high temperatures have come down 
</TEXT>
