<TEXT>
the metric system was born in the french revolution which also 
tried and failed to create the 10day week 
the intent was to give the citizen a fairer shake with weights 
and measures than the honesty of a merchants thumb on the scale 
the paris academy of sciences decided to base the system on a 
constant physical dimension in this case one tenmillionth of the 
arc from the north pole to the equator on a meridian passing 
through paris that unit was to be called a meter from the greek 
word metron for measure 
the liter was to be the volume of a cube onetenth meter on a 
side the gram the weight of pure water at a certain temperature 
in a cube onehundredth of a meter on a side all variations of 
these basic measurements were to be to the base 10 to simplify 
their use in arithmetic 
almost at once the meter was in hot water surveyors measuring 
the distance on the meridian from dunkirk to barcelona used white 
flags as markers white was the color of the monarchists who were 
soon to see their king beheaded the surveyors kept having to talk 
their way out of jail explaining they were just inventing the 
metric system not showing support for louis xvi 
the paris assembly adopted their work in 1791 thomas jefferson 
proposed a similar decimal system a few years later when he was 
secretary of state 
the french made metrics mandatory in 1840 the us congress 
declared the system legal in 1866 in 1875 the treaty of the meter 
was signed by the united states and 16 other nations creating an 
international bureau of weights and measures near paris 
since 1893 the american yard and pound have been based on the 
meter and kilogram but the united states has yet to officially 
convert to metrics it and burma are the only nations in the world 
not to have done so 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
