editors note camel caravans still wend across the sahara 
desert in northern niger as they have done for centuries but 
droughts in this decade have wiped out most livestock herds 
putting an end to the wandering of the nomadic tuaregs in villages 
such as agadez many have been reduced to hawking jewelry to 
tourists or scratching a meager garden out of the sand 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the evening call to prayer from a medieval 
minaret echoes through the sand streets to a market stall next to 
the sultans palace where abdou amadou sells nomad souvenirs and 
dreams of hondas 
the souvenirs are mere remnants of a fabulous desert culture 
that once flourished in agadez then a bustling crossroad of the 
great transsaharan trade 
the village is now an impoverished outpost in the landlocked 
west african nation of niger one of the poorest and most anonymous 
countries on earth but agadez manages to survive living off the 
legacy of the saharas golden age 
abdou 16 is watching the shop while his grandfather prays on a 
straw mat outside in the street two tourists browse through the 
sabers jewelry and camel saddles hanging on the wall 
its nomad abdou says pointing to a bracelet its 
silver ill make you a good price 
as the tourists walk away abdou says in french i want to 
sell enough to buy a honda someday and do a motorcross it would be 
marvelous his grandfather returns and speaking quietly in 
tamanjek tells abdou to get back to work 
tamanjek is the language of the tuareg nomads who for a 
thousand years lived and wandered in the onceborderless sahara 
desert that is now northern niger 
crafts and caravans as well as tourism are essential 
structural supports for the economy of northern niger a country 
with a population of about 7 million and an average per capita 
income of 270 a year 
the caravan route to timbuktu originated in agadez and was 
followed by arabs turks and egyptians the wealthy traders of the 
medieval world including a few europeans kept agents in agadez to 
expedite the flow of goods south to black africa and north to the 
mediterranean ports 
the gateway to the sahara agadez linked europe and africa 
white world and black the route came to symbolize the mystery of 
africa 
throughout the middle ages and continuing until two centuries 
ago huge caravans crisscrossed the desert waste sometimes lines 
of up to 40000 camels stretched to the shimmering horizon tuareg 
nomads proud and independent served as escorts camel handlers 
and guides across the unmarked sand nomad craftsmen made saddles 
sabers and other gear for the trail while other tuaregs bred camels 
to replace those lost to exhaustion and thirst 
crossing the desert was a complicated and dangerous business 
tens of thousands of human and animal skeletons lie buried beneath 
the sand whole convoys died from lack of water or heat or fell 
victim to bandits black africans perished on the forced march 
north to slavery or were worked to death more slowly in the desert 
salt pits 
the pits not far from agadez near the libyan border are still 
being worked although not by slaves and the transport still is 
handled in the cool winter months by camel caravans scores of 
caravans carry salt to feed the livestock of farmers in the more 
fertile south to the north they return with millet dates and 
wheat 
caravans appear suddenly from behind dunes like an illustration 
from arabian nights or frames from a hollywood foreign legion film 
the camels glide across the top of dunes tied in a line their 
hooves trailing plumes of sand beside them walk the nomads in 
robes that billow like sails in the wind from their belts swing 
curved carved sabers symbols of the tuaregs warrior past 
the caravan trade still feeds some families but many tuaregs in 
agadez have been reduced to hawking jewelry to tourists or 
scratching a meager garden out of the sand droughts in this decade 
have wiped out most herds putting an end to the nomads wandering 
and livelihood government policies that encourage the nomads to 
settle down have accelerated the change to a sedentary life 
</TEXT>
