<TEXT>
the sweeping capitalist revolution in britain is 
prime minister margaret thatchers 
but her top treasury official chancellor of the exchequer nigel 
lawson is the architect of the astounding turnaround in britains 
economy the worlds fifth largest 
once an economic laughing stock plagued by strikes high 
interest rates and inflation that coined the phrase the british 
disease britain is in its seventh consecutive year of economic 
growth and expanding faster than most of its major trading partners 
at a projected 3 percent in 1988 britains growth will outstrip 
the united states 23 percent and west germanys 17 percent and 
stand second only to japans 42 percent 
the base lending rate is down from a peak of 16 percent in 1981 
to 85 percent the annual inflation rate has been reined in from 
18 percent in 1980 to 4 percent last year 
now with a budget unveiled march 15 that will radically reform 
the tax structure lawsons accomplishments as the main architect 
of mrs thatchers economic policies rank him as one of britains 
boldest and most respected chancellors 
i think you can certainly say that certainly in the postwar 
period said ian harwood a chief economist at the london 
investment firm warburg securities 
he compares well with other chancellors said diane coyoe a 
british economist with the private forecasting firm dri europe 
hes been a very handson chancellor so he has to get a lot of 
the credit for it 
she added he will certainly be well remembered 
lawsons opponents in the socialistic labor party disagree they 
shouted down his budget speech when he announced big tax cuts for 
high earners and one was expelled from the house of commons for 
calling his strategy an utter obscenity 
lawsons fifth budget marked his zenith with the nineyearold 
conservative governments biggest tax reform 
reducing the income tax categories from six to two he slashed 
the rate for britains highest income earners from 60 percent to 
40 and set a basic rate of 25 percent the lowest since 1938 
in a testament to the governments tight fiscal spending 
policies 198788 produced the first budget surplus in almost 20 
years 
rich mans budget stormed the opposition laborites but a 
large conservative majority in the house of commons assures its 
passage 
lawson proudly predicted another year of healthy and 
noninflationary economic growth despite the october stock 
markets crash and repeated his common boast 
the british economy is stronger than at any time since the 
war we have followed the right policies and stuck to them 
the governments critics say that if this is a success story 
the price is too high 
they say the poor the unemployed and the sick have been 
abandoned by fiscal spending policies short on social conscience 
mrs thatcher argues that only a strong economy can protect the 
weak 
the critics also maintain that unemployment at a rate of 91 
percent is too high lawson notes it was above 11 percent 18 
months ago 
economists also worry about the trade deficit which is expected 
to triple to 74 billion in 1988 
britains surplus in oil trade which was 74 billion in 1987 
equal to the expected trade deficit disguises the real extent of 
the countrys trade imbalance the critics say 
they also contend that falling oil prices played a significant 
part in slowing the growth rate from 45 percent last year to the 
projected 3 percent 
lawsons critics also say manufacturing output hasnt fully 
recovered from the recession of the early 1980s it will grow by 
55 percent in 1988 lawson said but the governments most recent 
manufacturing output index stood at 1135 in january still below 
its record 1168 in june 1974 
in addition the labor unrest that mrs thatcher had curbed with 
laws limiting union power has picked up with a variety of strikes 
in recent months 
but the government says 339 million work days were lost to 
strikes last year up from a 34year low of 192 million in 1986 
but much lower than the 1970s average 
lawson like mrs thatcher doesnt waver from his agenda which 
has the prime ministers almost unqualified endorsement 
he has held his own opinions and followed them ms coyoe 
said 
his relationship with mrs thatcher is not always harmonious 
however just before budget day they disagreed over how much the 
government should intervene to stem the increase in the value of 
the british pound against other major currencies 
mrs thatcher stood by her freemarket convictions while lawson 
feared that without intervention a strong pound would hurt 
britains exports and corporate profits 
short boyishfaced chubby with a shock of black hair and a 
tart sense of humor lawson is the son of a jewish latvian 
immigrant who became a london tea merchant 
lawson graduated from oxford university in economics politics 
and philosophy and was a journalist before being elected to 
parliament in 1974 in 1979 he became a junior treasury minister in 
mrs thatchers first government 
he became chancellor in 1983 the first trained economist to 
hold the post since 1951 and began as a monetarist vowing to 
extinguish inflation by controlling the growth in britains money 
supply and government borrowing 
today he is a supplysider who advocates tax cuts and restrained 
fiscal spending supplyside economists believe increasing the 
money available for investment will boost productivity 
lawson lives with his second wife and two young children at 11 
downing st next door to the thatchers at no 10 
despite being credited with a large part in winning mrs 
thatcher her third consecutive term of office lawsons political 
future is uncertain critics say the chancellor is not sociable 
enough to garner support to lead the party in the unlikely event 
that the unflagging mrs thatcher would step down 
i think he would make a very good prime minister harwood 
said whether he would have a chance is another question 
the british press has speculated that after five years in the 
thatcher cabinet lawson is tired and frustrated and might take a 
lucrative job in the city londons financial district 
lawson says that while his tax reform is complete it is too 
soon to say whether he will be presenting next years budget 
</TEXT>
