<DOCNO> AP880321-0267 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
unionists at the beijing no 1 machine tool plant 
recently decided the factory manager had not been duly rewarded for 
his hard work and voted to increase his annual bonus 
that was one example boasted zheng lanjun head of the 
7200member union of how unions in socialist china strive to 
serve rather than confront the system 
but that cozy relationship under the firm guidance of the 
communist party is changing 
chinas bold economic reforms including giving factory bosses 
the authority to hire and fire workers have forced unions to 
redefine their role and even infused them with a touch of 
militancy 
with party approval unions are becoming more democratic less 
subservient to the party and more vocal on such issues as wages and 
worker safety 
the reforms have brought prosperity to the country and 
benefits to workers shen zuying spokesman for the allchina 
federation of trade unions said in an interview but they have 
also created new tasks for the unions as protectors of workers 
interests 
shen related how a union in wuhan central china recently 
fought back when the manager fired six workers for breaking factory 
rules it managed to get five reinstated he said 
in the northeast city of tianjin workers at a factory exercised 
their newfound power to oversee company operations by casting a 
noconfidence vote against the factory manager he was reassigned 
to the plants library 
the government has sanctioned a more assertive union movement to 
balance the growing power of factory managers under reforms that 
make industry more competitive and end lifetime employment 
guarantees 
beijing is giving factory heads greater freedom and 
responsibility over profits and losses and promoting job contracts 
that tie wages to performance few workers ever get fired but for 
the first time employees face discipline and possible dismissal 
for loafing on the job 
communist party chief zhao ziyang has called on unions to wake 
up to the new realities and play a greater supervisory role 
over the activities of their now powerful bosses 
for a long time trade unions were only involved in trifles 
distributing film tickets or relief aid to needy workers the 
official xinhua news agency said they played a small role in 
political issues 
that wasnt all the unions fault the allchina federation of 
trade unions made up of 15 union groupings with a membership of 90 
million or 90 percent of chinese factory workers dates back to 
1926 but since the communists came to power in 1949 and proclaimed 
the dictatorship of the proletariat the unions have been relegated 
to carrying out the party line on the factory floor 
in the 1950s unions were accused of syndicalism or trying 
to dominate the government and unions were disbanded during the 
ultraleftist 196676 cultural revolution 
the right of workers to strike was deleted from the 1982 
constitution 
the leaders didnt think it was necessary said the acftus 
shen we are socialists and the countrys interests and those of 
workers are the same 
he added however that strikes are not illegal and that if a 
strike is found to be justified we should support it such 
cases he said have been very rare 
instead unions are focusing on gaining a greater say in factory 
decisions 
workers in many plants nominate and elect their union 
representatives called workers congresses the congresses or 
their leaders must in turn be consulted by the factory manager 
before major decisions are made particularly on personnel matters 
party officials are supposed to let the unions run their own 
daytoday affairs although they still hold seats on union 
committees and are expected to guide the ideological thinking of 
workers 
in the past the party interfered too much in our 
activities shen said 
the union at the beijing no 1 machine tool plant besides 
organizing badminton tournaments and calligraphy classes is 
increasingly called on to mediate worker disputes zheng said 
he related how the union was the arbiter when a woman caught 
stealing was fired and when a man who lost both legs in an 
accident was unhappy with managements compensation of a new 
apartment television and refrigerator in both cases the union 
came down on the side of management 
but the union also has demanded that the factory do something 
about its unsanitary dining hall and is pushing for the factory to 
provide physical examinations more frequently than the current once 
every four years 
the trade union should support the director in exercising his 
rights and at the same time protect the rights of workers zheng 
said 
the acftus monopoly over organized labor is not likely to 
change in 1981 some young people tried to establish independent 
unions modeled after polands solidarity but they were quickly 
suppressed 
although union membership is technically voluntary almost 
everybody joins zheng said the 100 nonunion workers in the 
7300worker plant are new employees who havent put their 
applications in yet 
but the acftus shen noted that the reforms also have created 20 
million private businessmen and 80 million workers in small rural 
factories who are largely unorganized these groups he said may 
be the union movements next big challenge 
</TEXT>
