an investment group that owns an 11 percent 
stake in kansas city southern industries inc said monday it was 
offering 60 a share or about 594 million for the rest of the 
railroad concerns common stock 
kansas city southern which also has interests in financial 
services said its board would consider the allcash proposal soon 
at a special meeting 
the company has nearly 111 million shares outstanding and the 
investment group led by howard kaskel claims it controls about 12 
million shares 
in trading on the new york stock exchange kansas city southern 
jumped 875 a share to 55 
kaskel outlined the merger proposal in a letter to landon h 
rowland president and chief executive of kansas city southern and 
requested an opportunity to negotiate all aspects of the offer 
including price 
he said completing the proposal was subject to reaching a 
definitive agreement approval by the requisite number of directors 
and stockholders and satisfaction of all regulatory requirements 
but he warned that if the companys board rejected or failed to 
act on the offer by april 4 we will be forced to commence a 
proxy contest to elect directors who will actively pursue and 
encourage the maximization of stockholder values 
kaskel said he had made various proposals to company management 
over the past eight months on ways to maximize shareholder values 
unfortunately you have rejected each of my suggestions 
kaskel wrote 
in addition he said he found it dismaying that the board 
erected obstacles designed to entrench itself and to prevent 
stockholders from realizing a full return on their investment 
among these steps kaskel cited the recent issuance of about 14 
million shares or almost 15 percent of the companys 
thenoutstanding common stock to employee stock ownership plans at 
49 a share 
this could only have been motivated by the boards desire to 
place substantial voting power in its hands as a means of 
opposing proposals that may be brought before its shareholders 
the letter said 
kaskel also cited kansas city southerns continued efforts to 
acquire the southern pacific railroad despite southern pacifics 
binding agreement for its sale to the denver rio grande 
responding to the offer rowland said in a statement from 
company headquarters in kansas city that the company had received a 
merger proposal from kaskel and that it would be considered by the 
companys board at a special meeting to be held shortly 
he said the company would have no further comment until the 
board of directors had an opportunity to study the proposal 
kansas city southern owns the kansas city southern railroad 
which operates on about 1500 miles of track in missouri arkansas 
oklahoma kansas louisiana and texas 
it also owns 87 percent of dst systems inc a kansas citybased 
concern that provides data systems and recordkeeping services for 
mutual funds insurance companies and other financial services 
providers 
